So that was a tour de force.

00:32:16.950 --> 00:32:18.070
That was a magic moment.

00:32:18.070 --> 00:32:19.970
That was when you open
the champagne.

00:32:19.970 --> 00:32:22.430
It's not what you expected, of
course, because when I say

00:32:22.430 --> 00:32:25.280
imagine a robot wandering around
in [? Tech Square ?]

00:32:25.280 --> 00:32:28.160
picking up Coke cans, that
leaves open a huge envelope of

00:32:28.160 --> 00:32:30.120
possible hallucinations.

00:32:30.120 --> 00:32:33.930
And usually or hallucinations
about these things are--

00:32:33.930 --> 00:32:38.590
we imagine things to be more
fluid, more natural, and more

00:32:38.590 --> 00:32:39.780
impressive than they
actually are.

00:32:39.780 --> 00:32:43.680
But that was impressive, because
no robot came close to

00:32:43.680 --> 00:32:45.655
doing anything like
that before.

00:32:49.030 --> 00:32:50.740
More to be said about
that during the

00:32:50.740 --> 00:32:53.060
business lecture on Wednesday.

00:32:56.000 --> 00:32:58.810
So that's the subsumption
architecture.

00:32:58.810 --> 00:33:06.230
By the way, maybe at this point
we can say something

00:33:06.230 --> 00:33:10.020
about how the other
architectures relate to what

00:33:10.020 --> 00:33:12.460
Minsky was talking about.

00:33:12.460 --> 00:33:18.270
What's this deliberative
thinking layer correspond to?

00:33:18.270 --> 00:33:24.370
That's what SOAR is about,
and maybe GPS.

00:33:27.020 --> 00:33:30.200
So what's subsumption about?

00:33:30.200 --> 00:33:31.860
It's about stuff down here.

00:33:38.400 --> 00:33:42.685
It's about instinctive reaction
and learned reaction.

00:33:55.290 --> 00:33:59.120
But shoot, what about Minsky's
other layers?

00:33:59.120 --> 00:34:02.180
If we're going to be building
systems that are as smart as

00:34:02.180 --> 00:34:04.390
those things then we have to
worry a little bit about that

00:34:04.390 --> 00:34:05.710
sort of thing too.

00:34:05.710 --> 00:34:09.080
So that brings us to the
genesis architecture.

00:34:09.080 --> 00:34:12.679
And now let me give you the
standard caution that should

00:34:12.679 --> 00:34:15.500
be early in the presentation
of any academic.

00:34:15.500 --> 00:34:19.940
I will sometimes say "I," and
what I mean is "we." And

00:34:19.940 --> 00:34:23.540
sometimes I'll say "we," and
what I mean is "they." This

00:34:23.540 --> 00:34:27.739
was a system that was developed
mostly by students

00:34:27.739 --> 00:34:31.280
of mine who persuaded me, after
a great deal of time,

00:34:31.280 --> 00:34:34.420
that they were thinking the
right kinds of thoughts.

00:34:34.420 --> 00:34:38.469
But here's how the genesis
architecture works.

00:34:38.469 --> 00:34:43.940
As no surprise, given recent
discussions, it's all centered

00:34:43.940 --> 00:34:45.190
on language.

00:34:50.429 --> 00:34:54.880
And the language part of the
genesis system has two roles,

00:34:54.880 --> 00:34:59.910
one of which is to guide, and
marshal, and interact with the

00:34:59.910 --> 00:35:01.160
perceptual systems.

00:35:07.230 --> 00:35:14.645
And the other is to enable the
description of events.

00:35:36.980 --> 00:35:37.610
That's how it works.

00:35:37.610 --> 00:35:41.372
So is perception important?

00:35:41.372 --> 00:35:43.290
I don't know.

00:35:43.290 --> 00:35:47.130
I might ask you a question like,
is there anybody sitting

00:35:47.130 --> 00:35:50.440
in the front row wearing
blue jeans?

00:35:50.440 --> 00:35:52.410
And it's hard for you to
resist, under those

00:35:52.410 --> 00:35:55.370
circumstances, your eyes from
going over there and answering

00:35:55.370 --> 00:35:56.350
the question.

00:35:56.350 --> 00:35:58.180
Your eyes answer the question.

00:35:58.180 --> 00:36:02.780
No symbol processing system is
involved, except in so far as

00:36:02.780 --> 00:36:05.600
my language system has
communicated with their

00:36:05.600 --> 00:36:08.540
language system, which drives
your motor system and your

00:36:08.540 --> 00:36:10.690
vision system to go over
there and answer the

00:36:10.690 --> 00:36:13.490
question for you.

00:36:13.490 --> 00:36:16.980
But it's not just the real stuff
that the language system

00:36:16.980 --> 00:36:18.040
directs your attention to.

00:36:18.040 --> 00:36:20.970
It's also the imagined stuff.

00:36:20.970 --> 00:36:22.160
It's been a long semester.

00:36:22.160 --> 00:36:25.010
Have I told you the story
about my table saw?

00:36:25.010 --> 00:36:25.580
Probably not.

00:36:25.580 --> 00:36:26.120
Here's the deal.

00:36:26.120 --> 00:36:27.630
I bought a table saw.

00:36:27.630 --> 00:36:29.560
It's a wonderful table saw.

00:36:29.560 --> 00:36:30.940
I was installing it with
a friend of mine

00:36:30.940 --> 00:36:33.190
who's a cabinet maker.

00:36:33.190 --> 00:36:37.910
He said, never wear gloves
when you operate the saw.

00:36:37.910 --> 00:36:39.950
"Why?" I said.

00:36:39.950 --> 00:36:41.900
Before he could answer the
question I figured it out.

00:36:41.900 --> 00:36:43.540
Can you figure out why you never
wear gloves when you

00:36:43.540 --> 00:36:45.450
operate a table saw?

00:36:45.450 --> 00:36:46.930
You know what a table
saw is, right?

00:36:46.930 --> 00:36:48.650
It's a table with a spinning
blade in the middle.

00:36:48.650 --> 00:36:51.640
And you use it to cut wood.

00:36:51.640 --> 00:36:55.095
Why should you never
wear gloves?

00:36:55.095 --> 00:36:55.582
Yes?

00:36:55.582 --> 00:36:56.560
STUDENT: Well--

00:36:56.560 --> 00:36:57.770
STUDENT: --Well, you
know the answer.

00:36:57.770 --> 00:36:59.170
Ha, that's not fair.

00:36:59.170 --> 00:37:00.230
That's old Brett up there.

00:37:00.230 --> 00:37:03.180
He's heard the story
too many times.

00:37:03.180 --> 00:37:05.042
Yes, Andrew, you got it.

00:37:05.042 --> 00:37:06.810
STUDENT: I've been told
the answer before.

00:37:06.810 --> 00:37:07.960
PROFESSOR: You've been
told the answer.

00:37:07.960 --> 00:37:09.740
How about somebody who hasn't
been told the answer.

00:37:09.740 --> 00:37:10.130
Yes?

00:37:10.130 --> 00:37:11.920
STUDENT: Because the gloves
might get caught.

00:37:11.920 --> 00:37:14.410
PROFESSOR: Because the glove
might get caught and pull your

00:37:14.410 --> 00:37:15.670
hand into the blade.

00:37:15.670 --> 00:37:16.920
And then what happens?

00:37:19.140 --> 00:37:19.740
It's horrible.

00:37:19.740 --> 00:37:23.360
You're hand gets mangled and
your fingers get cut off, and

00:37:23.360 --> 00:37:26.300
this happens a lot
to professionals.

00:37:26.300 --> 00:37:28.790
It won't actually happen with
that table saw that I bought,

00:37:28.790 --> 00:37:33.130
because its play detects flesh
and stops the blade, which

00:37:33.130 --> 00:37:35.250
then leads to stopping the blade
and having the blade

00:37:35.250 --> 00:37:38.140
retreat into the table in
about two microseconds--

00:37:38.140 --> 00:37:39.590
two milliseconds.

00:37:39.590 --> 00:37:42.460
So, in general though, it's a
bad idea, and you always have

00:37:42.460 --> 00:37:46.490
to suppose that the mechanism
isn't working anyway in order

00:37:46.490 --> 00:37:48.320
to use good safety practice.

00:37:48.320 --> 00:37:50.170
But here's an example of
something that nobody ever

00:37:50.170 --> 00:37:53.560
told you that he was able to
figure out, by imagining what

00:37:53.560 --> 00:37:56.815
would happen and reading the
answers off of the scene that

00:37:56.815 --> 00:37:58.420
he imagined.

00:37:58.420 --> 00:38:02.260
So nobody ever says many of the
things that we know, but

00:38:02.260 --> 00:38:03.000
we know them anyway.

00:38:03.000 --> 00:38:04.330
Here's another example.

00:38:04.330 --> 00:38:05.650
Imagine running down
the street with a

00:38:05.650 --> 00:38:06.550
full bucket of water.

00:38:06.550 --> 00:38:09.190
What happens?

00:38:09.190 --> 00:38:12.110
The water splashes out and
gets your leg wet, right?

00:38:12.110 --> 00:38:14.500
You won't find that in
Open Minds database.

00:38:14.500 --> 00:38:16.630
Nobody ever said that
over the web.

00:38:16.630 --> 00:38:17.620
It's not written
down anywhere.

00:38:17.620 --> 00:38:19.040
But you know it.

00:38:19.040 --> 00:38:22.710
Because you, we human beings
have the capacity to imagine

00:38:22.710 --> 00:38:27.090
perceptual things and read the
answers to questions off of

00:38:27.090 --> 00:38:30.940
our imaginations with that
perceptual apparatus.

00:38:30.940 --> 00:38:35.020
So that's a very important
connection down there.

00:38:35.020 --> 00:38:38.150
And then if you've got the
ability to describe events,

00:38:38.150 --> 00:38:40.930
then you've got the ability to
tell and understand stories.

00:38:45.180 --> 00:38:48.030
And if you can do that, then you
can start to get a handle

00:38:48.030 --> 00:38:56.160
on culture, both macro
and micro.

00:38:58.790 --> 00:39:04.500
And by macro culture I mean the
country you grew up in,

00:39:04.500 --> 00:39:06.320
the religion you grew up with.

00:39:06.320 --> 00:39:09.290
And by micro I mean your
family and personal

00:39:09.290 --> 00:39:11.680
experience, and all
shades in between.

00:39:14.570 --> 00:39:18.520
So I don't know, what inspires
me and my associates to think

00:39:18.520 --> 00:39:19.250
in these terms?

00:39:19.250 --> 00:39:21.800
We talked about a little bit of
it last time when I talked

00:39:21.800 --> 00:39:27.060
about evolution and the apparent
flowering of our

00:39:27.060 --> 00:39:30.140
species about 50,000
years ago, at

00:39:30.140 --> 00:39:32.300
which time we got something.

00:39:32.300 --> 00:39:34.940
And I believe that
what we got--

00:39:34.940 --> 00:39:37.260
and this is the characterization
of this

00:39:37.260 --> 00:39:40.540
particular hypothesis--

00:39:40.540 --> 00:39:45.130
what we got is the ability
to tell stories

00:39:45.130 --> 00:39:46.980
and understand them.

00:39:46.980 --> 00:39:52.540
So if we want to label this
representation, it's the label

00:39:52.540 --> 00:39:55.840
strong story hypothesis.

00:40:02.200 --> 00:40:03.530
So what's the weak
story hypothesis?

00:40:03.530 --> 00:40:06.540
The weak story hypothesis
is, this is important.

00:40:06.540 --> 00:40:11.260
The strong story hypothesis
is, this is all there is.

00:40:11.260 --> 00:40:14.190
But is there any other evidence
of this is really,

00:40:14.190 --> 00:40:15.670
really, really important?

00:40:15.670 --> 00:40:20.520
So I've queried Krishna here
before the class starts, and

00:40:20.520 --> 00:40:23.560
he tells me I haven't told
you about the following

00:40:23.560 --> 00:40:24.850
experiment.

00:40:24.850 --> 00:40:28.300
This, in my way of thinking, is
the most important series

00:40:28.300 --> 00:40:32.720
of experiments ever done in
cognitive psychology,

00:40:32.720 --> 00:40:35.550
developmental psychology,
actually.

00:40:35.550 --> 00:40:39.090
So here's how we get started.

00:40:43.380 --> 00:40:48.070
There's a rectangular room,
if you're a person.

00:40:48.070 --> 00:40:51.490
If you're a rat, it's
a rectangular box.

00:40:51.490 --> 00:40:53.720
All the walls are
painted white.

00:40:53.720 --> 00:40:55.610
Are you with me so far?

00:40:55.610 --> 00:41:02.360
So now, in each corner there's
a basket, or cloth, or

00:41:02.360 --> 00:41:10.320
something in which or under
which you can put some food.

00:41:10.320 --> 00:41:15.055
Now, you put the food there
while the rat watches you.

00:41:18.550 --> 00:41:26.540
And then you give the rat a
little spin to disorient it.

00:41:26.540 --> 00:41:28.790
All right?

00:41:28.790 --> 00:41:34.130
So then, the rest stops
and goes for the food.

00:41:34.130 --> 00:41:37.440
And you can keep track of
where the rat goes.

00:41:37.440 --> 00:41:41.070
And the rat goes with
approximate equal probability

00:41:41.070 --> 00:41:44.760
predominantly to those
two corners.

00:41:44.760 --> 00:41:46.096
So I'd have bet you
didn't know that

00:41:46.096 --> 00:41:48.040
rats were that smart.

00:41:48.040 --> 00:41:51.070
So they understand the
rectangular nature of the room

00:41:51.070 --> 00:41:52.880
and they don't go to the
diagonal corners where the

00:41:52.880 --> 00:41:55.090
food cannot be.

00:41:55.090 --> 00:41:58.390
So are these genius rats?

00:41:58.390 --> 00:42:00.050
Or maybe we're just rats
with big brains.

00:42:00.050 --> 00:42:02.550
Because we do the same thing.

00:42:02.550 --> 00:42:08.220
So if you repeat this experiment
and replace the rat

00:42:08.220 --> 00:42:14.470
with a small child, and then you
put a toy in there instead

00:42:14.470 --> 00:42:17.520
of food, and the rat--

00:42:17.520 --> 00:42:18.550
not the rat.

00:42:18.550 --> 00:42:24.600
The child is usually held in a
parent's arms, usually the

00:42:24.600 --> 00:42:26.780
child's mother--

00:42:26.780 --> 00:42:28.840
usually because they think that
if they participate in

00:42:28.840 --> 00:42:31.320
these experiments up there at
Harvard their kid will get

00:42:31.320 --> 00:42:34.290
into Harvard some day.

00:42:34.290 --> 00:42:37.015
So the kid goes to a diagonal
corner just like a rat.

00:42:39.860 --> 00:42:46.790
And then the next thing you do
is, you try an adult, maybe an

00:42:46.790 --> 00:42:48.890
MIT student.

00:42:48.890 --> 00:42:50.680
That way you can
use food again.

00:42:55.650 --> 00:42:58.330
And you get the same result.

00:42:58.330 --> 00:43:00.680
Who could be surprised?

00:43:00.680 --> 00:43:04.570
So rats, children, and human
adults, pretty much all the

00:43:04.570 --> 00:43:11.450
same with respect to this
experiment, until you paint

00:43:11.450 --> 00:43:13.440
one wall blue.

00:43:13.440 --> 00:43:16.370
Rats are not colorblind, in
case you're wondering.

00:43:16.370 --> 00:43:19.130
Then what happens?

00:43:19.130 --> 00:43:25.930
Well, if you pay one wall blue
the rat still goes with equal

00:43:25.930 --> 00:43:29.560
probability to the two
diagonal corners.

00:43:29.560 --> 00:43:33.370
If you paint one wall blue, the
child still goes to the

00:43:33.370 --> 00:43:37.230
two diagonal corners with
approximate equal probability.

00:43:37.230 --> 00:43:42.940
It's only us genius human
adults who go

00:43:42.940 --> 00:43:44.190
only to that corner.

00:43:46.870 --> 00:43:48.285
So this invites a couple
of questions.

00:43:51.690 --> 00:43:57.510
One of which is, when does
a child become an adult?

00:43:57.510 --> 00:43:58.760
Any ideas?

00:44:00.990 --> 00:44:04.185
[INAUDIBLE], what
do you think?

00:44:04.185 --> 00:44:06.610
STUDENT: [INAUDIBLE].

00:44:06.610 --> 00:44:08.630
PROFESSOR: You can pick a
number greater than 1

00:44:08.630 --> 00:44:14.620
and less than 10.

00:44:14.620 --> 00:44:16.024
[INAUDIBLE], what
do you think?

00:44:16.024 --> 00:44:16.860
STUDENT: Five?

00:44:16.860 --> 00:44:19.550
PROFESSOR: It's a pretty
good guess.

00:44:19.550 --> 00:44:21.920
Do you have siblings
at that age?

00:44:21.920 --> 00:44:23.980
It's a surprise but,
why is it five?

00:44:23.980 --> 00:44:25.480
Is it because--

00:44:25.480 --> 00:44:26.910
what does it relate to?

00:44:26.910 --> 00:44:30.450
Is there any correlate to the
onset of that ability?

00:44:30.450 --> 00:44:32.450
You might try everything, as
[INAUDIBLE] does, because

00:44:32.450 --> 00:44:35.250
she's extremely careful.

00:44:35.250 --> 00:44:40.340
So she's tried gender, she's
tried the onset of language,

00:44:40.340 --> 00:44:44.430
the appreciation of music,
handedness, and there's only

00:44:44.430 --> 00:44:46.530
one thing that matters.

00:44:46.530 --> 00:44:51.640
And that is that the child
becomes adult at that time

00:44:51.640 --> 00:44:54.440
when they start to use the word
left and right when they

00:44:54.440 --> 00:44:57.450
describe the world.

00:44:57.450 --> 00:44:59.700
Now I said that very carefully
because they understand left

00:44:59.700 --> 00:45:03.050
and right at an earlier age, but
they only have started to

00:45:03.050 --> 00:45:05.530
use the words left and right
when they describe the world

00:45:05.530 --> 00:45:10.900
at the time that they begin to
break this symmetry and go to

00:45:10.900 --> 00:45:13.560
the correct corner.

00:45:13.560 --> 00:45:16.140
Now for the next element of this
I need something to read.

00:45:16.140 --> 00:45:17.390
Has anyone got a
textbook handy?

00:45:22.720 --> 00:45:27.680
Ah, "China, an Illustrated
History."

00:45:27.680 --> 00:45:28.930
Now I need a volunteer.

00:45:30.875 --> 00:45:31.320
OK.

00:45:31.320 --> 00:45:32.440
Andrew, you want to do this?

00:45:32.440 --> 00:45:33.690
So here's what you're
going to do.

00:45:37.080 --> 00:45:38.270
You can stay there.

00:45:38.270 --> 00:45:40.520
But you need to stand up.

00:45:40.520 --> 00:45:42.750
So what I'm going to do is,
I'm going to read you a

00:45:42.750 --> 00:45:44.310
passage from this book.

00:45:44.310 --> 00:45:45.710
And I want you to say
it back to me at the

00:45:45.710 --> 00:45:47.260
same time I read it.

00:45:47.260 --> 00:45:51.610
It's as if you're doing
simultaneous translation,

00:45:51.610 --> 00:45:53.405
except it's English
to English.

00:45:56.970 --> 00:45:59.160
This things got words
I can't pronounce.

00:45:59.160 --> 00:46:01.080
OK, are you ready to go?

00:46:01.080 --> 00:46:02.220
All right.

00:46:02.220 --> 00:46:05.330
"When overwhelmed by the
magnitude of the problems he

00:46:05.330 --> 00:46:08.730
tackled, he began to suspect
that others were plotting

00:46:08.730 --> 00:46:14.600
against him or secretly
ridiculing him."

00:46:14.600 --> 00:46:15.420
Thank you very much.

00:46:15.420 --> 00:46:16.560
That's great.

00:46:16.560 --> 00:46:17.880
So you see, he could do it.

00:46:17.880 --> 00:46:18.880
Some people can't do it.

00:46:18.880 --> 00:46:21.360
At least it take a
little practice.

00:46:21.360 --> 00:46:22.780
But he did it.

00:46:22.780 --> 00:46:25.080
And guess what I've
done to him?

00:46:25.080 --> 00:46:29.080
I've reduced his intelligence
to that of a rat.

00:46:29.080 --> 00:46:36.930
Because if you do this
experiment with an adult human

00:46:36.930 --> 00:46:38.850
who's doing this simultaneous
English to English

00:46:38.850 --> 00:46:40.940
translation, they go with equal

00:46:40.940 --> 00:46:43.910
probability to the two corners.

00:46:43.910 --> 00:46:45.210
So what's happened?

00:46:45.210 --> 00:46:47.720
What's happened is
you've jambed

00:46:47.720 --> 00:46:50.930
their language processor.

00:46:50.930 --> 00:46:54.070
And when their language
processor is jambed they can't

00:46:54.070 --> 00:46:57.970
put the blue wall together with
the rectangular shape.

00:46:57.970 --> 00:47:00.290
So it seems to be that language
is the mediator of

00:47:00.290 --> 00:47:02.520
exactly the combinators you
need in order to build

00:47:02.520 --> 00:47:04.250
descriptions.

00:47:04.250 --> 00:47:06.870
Because they can't even put
those things together when

00:47:06.870 --> 00:47:09.870
their language processor is
jambed by the simultaneous

00:47:09.870 --> 00:47:13.670
translation phenomenon.

00:47:13.670 --> 00:47:17.310
So that brings us to the two
gold star ideas of the day.

00:47:17.310 --> 00:47:29.730
One is, if you want to make
yourself smarter you want to

00:47:29.730 --> 00:47:30.690
do those things--

00:47:30.690 --> 00:47:32.760
look, listen, draw, and talk.

00:47:32.760 --> 00:47:36.100
Because those are the particular
mechanisms that

00:47:36.100 --> 00:47:40.440
surround this area down here,
which is the center of what we

00:47:40.440 --> 00:47:43.120
do-- which is the center
of our thinking.

00:47:43.120 --> 00:47:45.140
So why do you take
notes in class?

00:47:45.140 --> 00:47:47.350
Now because you'll ever look at
them before, but because it

00:47:47.350 --> 00:47:51.980
forces the engagement
of your linguistic--

00:47:51.980 --> 00:47:53.390
of your linguistic, your motor,

00:47:53.390 --> 00:47:54.820
and your visual apparatus.

00:47:54.820 --> 00:47:56.520
And that makes you smarter,
because it's

00:47:56.520 --> 00:47:59.520
exercising that stuff.

00:47:59.520 --> 00:48:02.560
The second thing you can say, in
conclusion, especially from

00:48:02.560 --> 00:48:12.355
this experiment, is beware
of fast talkers.

00:48:16.820 --> 00:48:19.260
Why do you want to be aware
of fast talkers.

00:48:19.260 --> 00:48:22.430
It's not because they will
talk you into anything.

00:48:22.430 --> 00:48:24.940
It's because that when they talk
fast they're jambing your

00:48:24.940 --> 00:48:28.000
language processor and
you can't thing.

00:48:28.000 --> 00:48:32.600
That's why you want to be
aware of fast talkers.

00:48:32.600 --> 00:48:34.850
Because if they jamb your
language processor you won't

00:48:34.850 --> 00:48:38.200
thinking and you'll buy that
car, or you'll buy that drink,

00:48:38.200 --> 00:48:40.925
or you'll do any manner of
things that people who want

00:48:40.925 --> 00:48:45.272
you to do those things have
learned to do by talking to

00:48:45.272 --> 00:48:47.960
jamb your processor.

00:48:47.960 --> 00:48:49.620
So that completes what we're
going to do today.

00:48:49.620 --> 00:48:51.290
And I'll give you a
demonstration of some of this

00:48:51.290 --> 00:48:52.540
stuff on another occasion.

